24 Jul 2019 19:42






I remember when I was 14. I was in a coding class, one of those things parents would send their kids to over the summer. I don't think I really did very well (fuckin' ADHD), and in retrospect the things I would've learned there would've helped me later in life. The course itself isn't important right now.

My instructor was a very wise man who happened to be an old-time goon from Something Awful. We talked for a bit, and he was surprisingly engaging. Chalk it down to shared interest: both of us were pretty immersed in the putrid culture of the internet, him more so than I. Looking back, I think he saw something in me that shouldn't have been there, and tried (hopefully successfully!) to steer me out.

There were two things my instructor absolutely hated above all else: 4chan and memes. He'd been there for 4chan's inception, and was rightfully ashamed of what it had done (and this was 2010). He additionally hated the overproliferation of memes, of decapitated ideas torn and mutilated to fit a grim canvas. When I once told him I'd heard puns are the lowest form of comedy, he retorted that memes wore that grim crown instead.

I guess what I'm trying to say is that a pun based on a meme isn't enough to sell a joke. The build-up needs to be engaging, and this feels like the bare minimum needed to establish the punchline.








 and I'm not Robert Frost.






